<!DOCTYPE recipeml PUBLIC "-//FormatData//DTD RecipeML 0.5//EN" "http://www.formatdata.com/recipeml/recipeml.dtd">
<?xml-stylesheet href="recipe.xml" type="text/xsl"?>
<recipeml xmlns:xmlns="http://www.formatdata.com/recipeml/recipeml.dtd" xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" version="0.5">
  <meta content="Saturday September  8, 2007" name="DC.Date"/>
  <recipe id="minty_white_hot_chocolate">
    <head>
      <title>Minty White Hot Chocolate</title>
      <categories>
        <cat class="main">Drinks</cat>
        <cat class="sub">Hot</cat>
        <cat class="region">America</cat>
				<cat class="diet">Egg-free</cat>
				<cat class="diet">Gluten-free</cat>
				<cat class="diet">Nut-free</cat>
      </categories>
    </head>

    <description>Last winter, the local branch of a national bakery chain sold mint white hot chocolate. As this was a new item, they offered free samples. I don't pass up free, but it was so watery yet cloyingly sweet that I wished I had. I knew I could do better, and I think I have. Without the bitterness of cocoa, white chocolate can be overly sweet, but the astringency of the mint provides balance.</description>

    <ingredients system="US">
      <ing-div>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>2 1/2</qty>
            <unit>oz</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>white chocolate</item>
<!--2 1/2 oz. white chocolate-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>2</qty>
            <unit>Tb</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>sugar</item>
<!--2 Tb sugar-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt><unit>pinch</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>salt</item>
<!--pinch of salt-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>1</qty>
            <unit>qt</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>milk</item>
<!--1 qt milk-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <alt-ing>
            <amt>
              <qty>1/2</qty>
              <unit>tsp</unit>
            </amt>
            <item>mint extract</item>
<!--1/2 tsp mint extract-->
          </alt-ing>
          <alt-ing>
            <amt>
              <qty>1</qty>
              <unit>bag</unit>
            </amt>
            <item>herbal mint tea</item>
<!--1 herbal mint tea bag-->
          </alt-ing>
          <alt-ing>
            <amt>
              <qty>1</qty>
              <unit>Tb</unit>
            </amt>
            <item>mint leaves</item>
            <prep>crushed</prep>
<!--1 Tb mint leaves, crushed-->
          </alt-ing>
        </ing>
      </ing-div>
    </ingredients>
    <directions>
      <step>Finely grate or chop the white chocolate. Grated white chocolate will melt almost instantaneously.</step>
      <step>Heat the milk, sugar, salt and mint extract or leaves, but do not boil. If using crushed mint leaves, put the leaves in a large tea ball or a wrap securely in cheesecloth.</step>
      <step>Add the white chocolate and stir until melted and the drink is sufficiently minty.</step>
    </directions>
  </recipe>
</recipeml>
